description:
Two Eared Grebes (Podiceps nigricollis), photographed at the south end of Salt Pond A12, near Alviso Marina County Park in northern Santa Clara County, CA.   In the lead shot, the bird on the left is still in basic plumage, while the one on the right has mostly molted into alternate plumage.  Note the enlarged tuft of feathers on its crown, as well as the shock of gold feathers emanating from his red eye.

In the second and last shot of the set, I've zoomed in on the bird that is molting. Once again, note the enlarged tuft of feathers on its crown and the shock of golden feathers sweeping back from its red eye.  Eventually, that shock of golden feathers will fan out around the eye in a striking pattern, the face and chin will turn black, and the flanks will turn a warm, chestnut color (a few early smudges of which have already begun to appear).  The molt will likely have finished in a few weeks, when this bird makes its way back to its traditional summer breeding grounds, somewhere deep in the interior West of the United States and Canada.

The stems were light red, the leaves were large and green, and the bunches of yellow blooms were bold! It grew in the Sand Dunes.
The pine was large, yet low on the sand like a carpet. The needles were in bundles of three, and this is the only pine species inhabiting these Sand Dunes.
The plant was a medium size shrub with light shaded stems and small, thick leaves. This species grew rigorously in the patches of Sand Dunes.
This bird was curiously darting around the shrubs. The head had black and white stripes, and the beak was orange. It perched on the boardwalk crossing the Sand Dunes.

The flowering plant was very tiny and cute! The leaves were narrow, green, and at the base along the sand. The yellow flowers were in a spherical form. This small, yet precious jewel is one of the main successes of the restoration of the Asilomar Sand Dunes.
